{"cursor":"11485","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type = Bishop name = Juan JosÃ© Gerardi Conedera title = Auxiliary Bishop\n| of Diocese of Guatemala (Emeritus) image = Juan gerardi.jpg alt = caption\n| = church = Roman Catholic Church archdiocese = diocese = see = Archdiocese\n| of Guatemala term = 1984 - 1998 predecessor = successor = Mario Enrique\n| RÃ­os Montt\n\n| ordination = 21 December 1946 ordinated_by = consecration = consecrated_by\n| = rank =\n\n| birth_date = birth_place = Guatemala City, Guatemala death_date = death_place\n| = previous_post = Bishop of Santa Cruz del QuichÃ© (1974-1984)\n}}\n\n'[[Monsignor]] Juan JosÃ© Gerardi Conedera' (27 December 1922 â 26 April\n1998) was a Guatemalan Roman Catholic bishop and human rights\ndefender who was long active in working with the indigenous Mayan peoples of the\ncountry. In the 1970s he gained government recognition of indigenous languages\nas official languages, and helped secure permission for radio stations to\nbroadcast in indigenous languages. In 1988 he was appointed to the government's\nNational Reconciliation Commission, to begin the process of accounting for\nabuses during the civil war.\n\nHe also worked on the associated Recovery of Historical Memory Project (REMHI)\nsponsored by the Catholic Church. Two days after he announced the release of its\nreport on victims of the Guatemalan Civil War, Guatemala: Nunca MÃ¡s!, in April\n1998, Bishop Gerardi was attacked in his garage and beaten to death. In 2001, in\nthe first trial in civil court of members of the military in Guatemalan history,\nthree Army officers were convicted of his death and sentenced to long prison\nterms. A priest was convicted as an accomplice and also sentenced.\n","linknr":185,"url":"Juan_José_Gerardi_Conedera","recorded":1375071759,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Juan_Jos%C3%A9_Gerardi_Conedera&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Juan_Jos%C3%A9_Gerardi_Conedera&action=edit","//bi